                <h1>Gazelle Systems</h1>
                <p>
                    Around 1984, the enterpreneurial bug bit me.
                </p>
                <p>
                    I was the controller for a small company, Delstar Corporation, and thought they
                    needed some commercial software product that could help the company's sagging revenues. While at Delstar,
                    I had designed, written, and debugged a file manager I named
                    <cite><a href="https://books.google.com/books?id=yQc-6nkRfXMC&pg=PA214&lpg=PA214&dq=fileease+delstar&source=bl&ots=jv3ivrRELV&sig=naAW91oggCQNQNaO6pGGuD9HJA4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCEQ6AEwAGoVChMIrbe2_NSexwIVQ5MNCh3fkQB-#v=onepage&q=fileease%20delstar&f=false">FileEase</a></cite>
                    (using <cite><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turbo_Pascal">Turbo Pascal</a></cite> -- I loved that product!).
                    This was my first commercial product.
                </p>
                <p>
                    But I soon became frustrated with the
                    company being unable to pay me and realized it was time for me to leave.
                    I decided I would create a much better file manager,
                    but it had to be 10x faster. I had heard a lot about the C programming language and figured that was the ticket. I wasn't
                    really sure how to procede, but I knew I had to do it.
                </p>
                <p>
                    So it was off to the races. Around March 1985 I had very little money, but I figured my money could 
                    last until the end of the year. 
                    So in about 9 months, I taught myself C, 8088 assembly language, DOS internals, and
                    learned several BIOS hooks. I also had to figure out some undocumented DOS calls. And then our first product was
                    ready to launch.
                </p>
                <p>
                    I relied on my dad for some marketing tips for our first ad. He asked me, "Eric, if you really think this new product
                    of yours is so great, why don't you offer a double-your-money-back guarantee?" So I thought, hmmm... why not? And so we did.
                    We actually ran an A/B split with our first InfoWorld ad. The first ad was a double-your-money-back ad. 
                    <a target="_blank" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=nC8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA41&lpg=PA41&dq=gazelle+systems+provo&source=bl&ots=cCYpyOjTGn&sig=dT3BBSPL3wM874N0bDmZm5iISCg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCwQ6AEwBDgKahUKEwiI0t_01OLGAhVKmoAKHTm_AGo#v=onepage&q=gazelle%20systems%20provo&f=false">
                        The second</a> was
                        a bit different: if you didn't like our product, tell us and we will refund your money and buy you the competitor's product
                        of your choice (a dangerous thing, as one of our competitors was priced at 3x our price).
</p>
                <p>
                    This was gutsy, but I knew that one of two things would absolutely happen:
                    <ol>
                        <li>We would get noticed immediately, and ...</li>
                        <li>We would either go bankrupt quickly, or soar.</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <p>
                    We soared! And we got into lots of debt, barely hung on, 
                    and then sold the company for a song. I got just over $30k for my ownership, after turning down an option a year
                    before that would have netted me around $9 million (live and learn, that's what life's about, right?!).
                </p>
                <p>
                    I was surprised to find there's quite a bit of information about this great company available online. 
                </p>

