                <h3 id="Back-It">Back-It</h3>
                <h4>Everybody needs to backup...</h4>
                <p>
                    We needed a second product, since we now had a working distribution channel. Next on my list: a solid backup product. And it had
                    to be fast.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Memory was scarce in those days (mid to late 1980s), everything had to fit in 64k of memory (you could use extended memory, but there were
                    many potential solutions, some of which even worked!) One of the tricks I learned is that if I used assembly language,
                    my code would be smaller than otherwise, leaving more RAM available for file buffers; and more and larger buffers, with an
                    intelligent algorithm, could always speed up the process substantially.
                </p>
                <p>
                    So I used the <a target="_blank" href="http://www.desmet-c.com/">DeSmet C compiler</a> which allowed me to switch in and out of C and assembly
                    language, which I totally loved doing. So I was able to write, debug, and create Gazelle's second product quite quickly.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Total elapsed time to conceive, design, build, debug, test, and ship: 2 months.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Later, I got my hands on some Intel reference books (they weighed a couple pounds each) so I could figure out how to program
                    the floppy-disk controller and the DMA chip. After about the 50th time thru around 100 pages, it finally started to sink in,
                    and I was able to more than quadruple the speed of backups by overlapping read and write I/O. Very, very cool technology.
                </p>
                <p>
                    I also conceived of and designed a test (that Intel quickly asked for) that detected flawed DMA chips thru software; 
                    seems under certain conditions when overlapping reads and writes, the data would shift by one byte position on a sector 
                    about to be written... nasty!
                </p>
